Here's a ChucK program that sends a one-second middle C triangle wave to the DAC:

```chuck
// Define frequency of middle C (approximately 261.63 Hz)
float freq = 261.63;

// Create a sine oscillator for phase generation
SinOsc sine => dac;

// Create a triangle wave using the sine oscillator and a mathematical transformation
// Triangle wave can be approximated using the arctangent function or by manipulating sine
// We'll use a common approximation: triangle = (2/pi) * asin(sin(omega * t))
// But for simplicity and accuracy, we can use a more direct method with a phase accumulator

// Alternatively, use a built-in triangle oscillator
TriangleOsc tri => dac;

// Set the frequency of the triangle wave
tri.freq(freq);

// Start the oscillator
tri => dac;

// Wait for 1 second
1::second => now;

// Stop the oscillator (optional, but good practice)
tri.halt();
```

